Description: Egyptian sealing in fired clay. A sealing impressed by two intaglio gems, one (stamped twice) with a human foot and an uncertain device, possibly a mattock, the other with Osiris-in-a-Jar to front. The back has an impression of the papyrus document to which it was attached, with a hole for the string that bound the package. Red-brown Nile silt with abundant mica and white inclusions.
Curator's comments: Found with BM1886,0401.1701 and 1700. Petrie dates this group as 2nd century AD (Petrie 1886,100, pl. XX nos 20-22). Clay resembles local Naukratis red Nile silt fabric, but could have been sent here from another location on the Nile Delta. '1' in pencil.
'1' written on in pencil. Site or context number?
